        <div n="664C14W2">
          <head type="note" n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-1">
            <lg n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-1-line-group-1" type="headnote">
              <l n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-1-line-group-1-line-1">ON THE BUSTS <ref target="#spp-664C14W2-footnote-headnote-1">1</ref><note n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-footnote-headnote-1" place="foot">Newton, Locke, Clarke, and Woolaston.── H</note> IN RICHMOND HERMITAGE.</l>
            </lg>
          </head>
          <head type="note" n="2" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-2">
            <lg n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-2-line-group-1" type="headnote">
              <l n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-2-line-group-1-line-1">1732.</l>
            </lg>
          </head>
          <head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-3">
            <lg n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote">
              <l n="1" xml:id="spp-664C14W2-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1">“Sic siti lætantur docti.”</l>
            </lg>
          </head>
          <lg n="1">
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-1" n="1">W<hi rend="small-caps">ITH</hi> honour thus by Carolina placed,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-2" n="2">How are these venerable bustoes graced!</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-3" n="3">O queen, with more than regal title crown'd,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-4" n="4">For love of arts and piety renown'd!</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-5" n="5">How do the friends of virtue joy to see</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-6" n="6">Her darling sons exalted thus by thee!</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-7" n="7">Nought to their fame can now be added more,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-664C14W2-line-8" n="8">Revered by her whom all mankind adore.<note place="foot">·Queen Caroline's regard for learned men was chiefly directed to those who had signalized themselves by philosophical research. Walpole alludes to this her peculiar taste, in his fable called the Funeral of the Lioness, where the royal shade is made to say,<lb/>Where Elysian waters glide,_With Clarke and Newton by her side,_She pores o'er metaphysic page.</note></l>
          </lg>
        </div>
      </div>
